00:19:24,235 --> 00:19:26,336
I got this job.

264
00:19:28,139 --> 00:19:31,508
Well, it's an internship,
actually.

265
00:19:31,510 --> 00:19:33,476
But it's a pretty big deal.
It's at a gallery in Manhattan.

266
00:19:35,012 --> 00:19:36,279
Okay.

267
00:19:38,983 --> 00:19:39,916
Uh...

268
00:19:41,285 --> 00:19:44,454
That's why it took me so long
to call you back.

269
00:19:44,456 --> 00:19:46,423
I just didn't think that this
would even be a good idea.

270
00:19:47,993 --> 00:19:49,426
I'm glad you did.

271
00:19:51,163 --> 00:19:52,429
Yeah?
Yeah.

272
00:19:56,034 --> 00:19:57,968
This is just bad timing.

273
00:19:59,236 --> 00:20:00,804
Yeah.

274
00:20:05,177 --> 00:20:06,510
Oh, I probably should
take you home.

275
00:20:08,246 --> 00:20:09,246
Gonna rain.

276
00:20:21,560 --> 00:20:22,527
Did you see that?

277
00:20:22,529 --> 00:20:23,929
What?

278
00:20:36,374 --> 00:20:37,408
Luke!

279
00:20:37,943 --> 00:20:39,443
What is it?

280
00:20:45,351 --> 00:20:47,118
Call 911!

281
00:20:55,494 --> 00:20:56,628
Hey!
Wake up!

282
00:20:56,630 --> 00:20:58,029
Is he alive?

283
00:20:58,031 --> 00:20:59,164
Here, hold this.

284
00:21:11,043 --> 00:21:12,043
Box.

285
00:21:13,479 --> 00:21:14,946
Box.

286
00:21:14,948 --> 00:21:16,148
What did he say?
"Box"?

287
00:21:46,647 --> 00:21:49,115
I think you just
saved that guy's life.

288
00:21:49,117 --> 00:21:50,950
We both did.

289
00:21:50,952 --> 00:21:52,519
Oh, come on,
I held the flashlight.

290
00:21:52,521 --> 00:21:54,488
You were amazing.

291
00:21:57,524 --> 00:21:59,358
I just hope that he's okay.

292
00:22:00,994 --> 00:22:02,628
I'll take you home.

293
00:22:03,964 --> 00:22:05,498
I think I'm going to stay.

294
00:22:05,500 --> 00:22:06,465
Really?

295
00:22:08,101 --> 00:22:10,370
Yeah, at least until he gets
out of the emergency room.

296
00:22:11,139 --> 00:22:12,239
Then I'll wait with you.

297
00:22:12,707 --> 00:22:14,441
No, it's fine.

298
00:22:14,443 --> 00:22:15,442
Really.

299
00:22:16,477 --> 00:22:18,512
And thank you for tonight.

300
00:22:19,948 --> 00:22:21,248
Yeah, it was a...

301
00:22:21,250 --> 00:22:23,116
It was a great night.

302
00:22:23,118 --> 00:22:24,251
Kind of.

303
00:22:27,456 --> 00:22:30,057
Good luck with
everything in New York.

304
00:22:30,059 --> 00:22:31,458
Mmm-hmm.

305
00:23:55,711 --> 00:23:58,647
"April 10th, 1940.

306
00:23:58,649 --> 00:24:01,150
<i>"My dearest Ruth...</i>

307
00:24:01,152 --> 00:24:04,653
<i>"Today started out
like any other day.</i>

308
00:24:04,655 --> 00:24:07,189
<i>"But when you walked in
to my father's store...</i>

309
00:24:07,191 --> 00:24:09,725
<i>"so beautiful, so vibrant...</i>

310
00:24:11,362 --> 00:24:13,462
<i>"I knew my life would
forever be changed. "</i>

311
00:24:17,668 --> 00:24:19,569
You are the new family
the Rabbi has told us about.

312
00:24:20,604 --> 00:24:21,504
From Vienna?

313
00:24:22,306 --> 00:24:23,405
Uh, yes.

314
00:24:23,407 --> 00:24:25,240
I am Hannah...

315
00:24:25,242 --> 00:24:27,476
and this is my daughter,
Ruth.

316
00:24:27,478 --> 00:24:28,744
Nice to meet you.

317
00:24:28,746 --> 00:24:30,813
I'm Sarah...

318
00:24:30,815 --> 00:24:33,616
and this is my son, Ira.

319
00:24:35,519 --> 00:24:36,619
Ira?

320
00:24:37,154 --> 00:24:38,354
Ira?

321
00:24:53,604 --> 00:24:55,138
<i>- Good Shabbes.
- Good Shabbes.</i>

322
00:25:02,146 --> 00:25:03,213
<i>Good Shabbes.</i>

323
00:25:04,548 --> 00:25:05,548
<i>Good Sha...</i>

324
00:25:07,418 --> 00:25:09,487
<i>The following days
were consumed...</i>

325
00:25:09,489 --> 00:25:12,556
<i>with plotting ways in which
I could talk to you...</i>

326
00:25:12,558 --> 00:25:15,292
<i>now that you had found a home
in my small community.</i>

327
00:25:39,684 --> 00:25:42,853
<i>But I wasn't the only one
seeking your attention.</i>

328
00:25:47,360 --> 00:25:49,327
<i>This would take
some more time.</i>

329
00:26:02,708 --> 00:26:04,442
He's awake,
if you'd like to see him.

330
00:26:04,444 --> 00:26:06,178
You have to eat something,
Mr. Levinson.

331
00:26:06,180 --> 00:26:07,512
It's the only way you're
going to get better.

332
00:26:07,514 --> 00:26:08,847
I'm old.

333
00:26:08,849 --> 00:26:10,615
I've had a heart attack...

334
00:26:10,617 --> 00:26:12,250
a hip replacement...

335
00:26:12,252 --> 00:26:13,485
surgery in both knees.

336
00:26:14,520 --> 00:26:16,354
How much better
am I going to get?

337
00:26:20,893 --> 00:26:21,860
Who are you?

338
00:26:23,462 --> 00:26:25,730
I, uh...
I came to drop this off.

339
00:26:25,732 --> 00:26:26,631
How'd you get that?

340
00:26:27,867 --> 00:26:29,401
From your car.

341
00:26:29,403 --> 00:26:31,236
You asked me
to get it for you.

342
00:26:31,704 --> 00:26:32,904
Oh, you...

343
00:26:34,373 --> 00:26:36,408
You pulled me out?

344
00:26:36,410 --> 00:26:38,411
No, my friend Luke
pulled you out...

345
00:26:38,413 --> 00:26:39,979
but you asked me to go
back and get this box.

346
00:26:43,383 --> 00:26:44,450
You don't remember?

347
00:26:44,585 --> 00:26:45,785
Hmm.

348
00:26:47,754 --> 00:26:49,854
Well, thank you.

349
00:26:51,591 --> 00:26:53,725
Very much.

350
00:26:53,727 --> 00:26:57,430
He seems to like you,
which is a first for him.

351
00:26:57,432 --> 00:26:59,532
See if you can get him to
eat something, would you?

352
00:27:01,902 --> 00:27:05,271
She has the coldest hands
I've ever felt.

353
00:27:06,473 --> 00:27:08,274
I think she soaks
them in ice water...

354
00:27:08,276 --> 00:27:09,675
before she comes by.

355
00:27:19,553 --> 00:27:21,520
You really should
eat something.

356
00:27:21,522 --> 00:27:22,788
I'm done.

357
00:27:34,769 --> 00:27:36,436
Is that what
Ruth would want?

358
00:27:39,807 --> 00:27:42,009
How do you know about Ruth?

359
00:27:42,011 --> 00:27:43,477
Did you read my letters?

360
00:27:43,479 --> 00:27:45,312
What do you care?

361
00:27:45,314 --> 00:27:46,680
You're done.

362
00:27:52,553 --> 00:27:54,421
They're beautiful.

363
00:28:00,795 --> 00:28:02,863
She was a beautiful woman.

364
00:28:06,367 --> 00:28:08,336
In every way.

365
00:28:11,507 --> 00:28:14,809
I can see why they were
so precious to you.

366
00:28:32,895 --> 00:28:35,997
I haven't been able
to read them for years.

367
00:28:35,999 --> 00:28:39,000
Even with my glasses.

368
00:28:39,002 --> 00:28:40,735
Do you want me
to read them to you?

369
00:28:52,081 --> 00:28:53,648
But you have to eat first.

370
00:29:11,768 --> 00:29:14,903
"May 25th, 1940.

371
00:29:14,905 --> 00:29:17,004
"For the first time in my life...

372
00:29:17,006 --> 00:29:21,043
"I was hoping the service at the
synagogue would be longer. "

373
00:29:31,621 --> 00:29:32,888
Excuse me.

374
00:29:43,135 --> 00:29:44,700
Are you ever going
to talk to me?

375
00:29:47,871 --> 00:29:49,671
Excuse me?

376
00:29:49,673 --> 00:29:51,707
I always see you there,
lurking around.

377
00:29:53,843 --> 00:29:55,043
I don't lurk.

378
00:29:55,045 --> 00:29:57,747
You do lurk.

379
00:29:57,749 --> 00:30:00,583
But then you never talk to me.
Am I so frightening?

380
00:30:01,685 --> 00:30:02,786
No, I...

381
00:30:08,627 --> 00:30:11,728
What you did to that poor
rose was unforgiveable.

382
00:30:13,698 --> 00:30:14,931
You saw that?

383
00:30:18,002 --> 00:30:20,770
Don't be embarrassed.
It was a lovely gesture.

384
00:30:20,772 --> 00:30:21,838
Ruthie?

385
00:30:24,041 --> 00:30:25,942
Want to walk me home?

386
00:30:26,911 --> 00:30:28,144
Oh...

387
00:30:28,146 --> 00:30:29,779
What about David Stein?

388
00:30:29,781 --> 00:30:31,549
He can walk my mother home.

389
00:30:34,487 --> 00:30:37,621
Vienna is beautiful
and so cultured.

390
00:30:37,623 --> 00:30:39,490
It has more artists than Paris.

391
00:30:40,759 --> 00:30:43,927
At least it did before the war.

392
00:30:43,929 --> 00:30:45,695
It must have been
hard for you to leave.

393
00:30:45,697 --> 00:30:46,863
Yeah.

394
00:30:48,799 --> 00:30:51,702
Especially for my parents.

395
00:30:51,704 --> 00:30:53,704
But it would have been worse
if we had stayed.

396
00:30:57,142 --> 00:30:59,143
Everyone thought
we were being foolish...

397
00:30:59,145 --> 00:31:02,246
that my father
was overreacting.

398
00:31:02,248 --> 00:31:03,714
Now we can't even contact
our relatives anymore.

399
00:31:07,820 --> 00:31:10,021
what right do I have
to be happy

400
00:31:10,023 --> 00:31:11,656
when there's so much
suffering in the world?

401
00:31:13,225 --> 00:31:15,626
I guess you could say, what right
do you have to be unhappy?

402
00:31:18,864 --> 00:31:20,664
True.

403
00:31:20,666 --> 00:31:23,200
For a country pumpkin,
you're quite philosophical.

404
00:31:25,238 --> 00:31:27,539
What?

405
00:31:27,541 --> 00:31:29,241
It's a "country bumpkin"
not a "country pumpkin. "

406
00:31:30,142 --> 00:31:31,176
What?

407
00:31:33,045 --> 00:31:34,913
I think I prefer the
way you said it.

408
00:31:40,686 --> 00:31:41,586
Well.

409
00:31:43,222 --> 00:31:45,590
Thank you for walking me home.

410
00:31:45,592 --> 00:31:47,192
Oh, you're welcome.

411
00:31:47,194 --> 00:31:48,693
It was a pleasure.

412
00:32:02,676 --> 00:32:03,676
Ruth...

413
00:32:07,781 --> 00:32:08,948
Do you want to go
out with me sometime?

414
00:32:12,018 --> 00:32:13,585
I'm free after Shabbat.

415
00:32:16,188 --> 00:32:17,856
Wait. You want
to go out tonight?

416
00:32:17,858 --> 00:32:19,992
We're not getting
any younger, Levinson.

417
00:32:21,828 --> 00:32:23,596
You can wait there
if you want.

418
00:32:31,706 --> 00:32:33,839
"Forever yours...

419
00:32:34,308 --> 00:32:35,575
"Ira. "

420
00:32:41,848 --> 00:32:42,982
You want me to read
you another one?

421
00:32:44,818 --> 00:32:45,851
Mmm.

422
00:32:49,056 --> 00:32:50,990
But...

423
00:32:52,593 --> 00:32:53,726
Could you maybe...

424
00:32:55,663 --> 00:32:57,130
Could you maybe come back?

425
00:33:08,242 --> 00:33:10,109
Carolina Thunder's
a good draw.

426
00:33:10,979 --> 00:33:15,682
<i>Savannah, Georgia fans,
put your hands together...</i>

427
00:33:15,684 --> 00:33:19,152
<i>for the one,
the only, Rango!</i>

428
00:33:29,931 --> 00:33:33,034
<i>We will move our attention down
to the Cooper Tires bucking chute...</i>

429
00:33:33,036 --> 00:33:37,271
<i>where Evan Matthews from Summerville,
Georgia is set to go.</i>

430
00:33:37,273 --> 00:33:40,407
<i>He is about to face a bull
that needs no introduction.</i>

431
00:33:40,409 --> 00:33:42,142
<i>85 consecutive buck-offs...</i>

432
00:33:48,082 --> 00:33:50,318
<i>He is going
for the Gold Buckle.</i>

433
00:34:00,863 --> 00:34:01,863
That looks familiar.

434
00:34:14,343 --> 00:34:16,344
<i>Let's go to Luke Collins.</i>

435
00:34:16,346 --> 00:34:19,747
<i>If he makes a qualified ride
on Carolina Thunder...</i>

436
00:34:19,749 --> 00:34:22,950
<i>he will crack the top 35 and
punch his ticket to Vegas!</i>

437
00:34:22,952 --> 00:34:23,851
Let's go!

438
00:34:31,394 --> 00:34:33,762
<i>He comes down too early</i>

439
00:34:33,764 --> 00:34:34,797
<i>in a costly mistake.</i>

440
00:34:34,799 --> 00:34:38,433
<i>A mistake that could cost him
a trip to the World Finals...</i>

441
00:34:38,435 --> 00:34:40,935
<i>and ultimately,
a World Title.</i>

442
00:34:40,937 --> 00:34:43,305
<i>You really gotta wonder...</i>

443
00:34:43,307 --> 00:34:45,240
<i>where this guy is
mentally right now.</i>

444
00:34:45,242 --> 00:34:47,242
<i>The incident with
Rango before he rode...</i>

445
00:34:47,244 --> 00:34:48,844
Good ride, Luke.

446
00:34:48,846 --> 00:34:50,447
<i>...has affected
his mental focus.</i>

447
00:35:04,495 --> 00:35:05,962
Damn it!

448
00:35:49,040 --> 00:35:51,508
Return of the conquering hero.

449
00:35:52,810 --> 00:35:54,178
Hey, Mom.

450
00:35:56,414 --> 00:35:58,182
You want eggs?
No.

451
00:36:00,452 --> 00:36:01,452
So, how did it go?

452
00:36:06,090 --> 00:36:08,124
Well, you left the ring
on your own two feet.

453
00:36:08,126 --> 00:36:10,260
So, it's a victory for me.

454
00:36:11,930 --> 00:36:13,097
When are you gonna
stop the bull riding, Luke?

455
00:36:15,233 --> 00:36:17,535
Mom, I told you, I can't.

456
00:36:17,537 --> 00:36:20,137
Really? So you forgot
about your head injury?

457
00:36:20,139 --> 00:36:21,438
I'm a grown man.

458
00:36:21,440 --> 00:36:23,007
I just want you to get
to be an old man.

459
00:36:25,277 --> 00:36:26,377
Thanks.

460
00:36:32,985 --> 00:36:34,119
You're scaring the
hell out of me, Luke.

461
00:36:35,153 --> 00:36:36,587
Please just give it up.
Don't worry.

462
00:36:42,060 --> 00:36:42,893
So, what's going on?

463
00:36:45,997 --> 00:36:47,298
Nothing.

464
00:36:49,602 --> 00:36:50,569
Nothing.

465
00:36:55,541 --> 00:36:57,442
I met a girl.

466
00:36:57,444 --> 00:36:59,010
You meet girls all the time.
No.

467
00:37:00,546 --> 00:37:03,048
This one's different.

468
00:37:05,151 --> 00:37:06,051
I can't stop
thinking about her.

469
00:37:06,586 --> 00:37:08,520
So?

470
00:37:08,522 --> 00:37:10,555
She moves to New York
in two months.

471
00:37:11,991 --> 00:37:15,360
So, I guess
that's that, right?

472
00:37:16,362 --> 00:37:18,263
You soak your hand
in ice water.

473
00:37:18,265 --> 00:37:18,997
I do no such thing.

474
00:37:18,999 --> 00:37:22,467
I'm the only person at the
hospital who still talks to you.

475
00:37:22,469 --> 00:37:23,368
Am I interrupting?

476
00:37:23,370 --> 00:37:26,339
I was just about to
strangle him! But...

477
00:37:26,341 --> 00:37:28,140
Strangle me before dinner...

478
00:37:28,142 --> 00:37:29,609
so I don't have to eat
another hospital meal.

479
00:37:29,611 --> 00:37:30,877
The sooner the better.

480
00:37:32,312 --> 00:37:33,278
Enjoy his letters.

481
00:37:37,049 --> 00:37:38,016
You look good.

482
00:37:40,553 --> 00:37:41,520
Shall we?

483
00:37:42,155 --> 00:37:43,122
Yeah.

484
00:38:00,675 --> 00:38:03,342
"July 12th, 1941. "
Oh.

485
00:38:06,948 --> 00:38:08,681
That was a good day.

486
00:38:12,119 --> 00:38:14,987
"Dearest Ruth, the memories
of our adventure...

487
00:38:16,390 --> 00:38:18,558
"are always dancing in my mind. "

488
00:38:18,560 --> 00:38:21,295
<i>Seems like yesterday...</i>

489
00:38:21,297 --> 00:38:24,064
<i>you helped me see the world
in a whole different way.</i>

490
00:38:24,066 --> 00:38:26,700
all dressed up just
to go to a movie.

491
00:38:26,702 --> 00:38:29,336
In Vienna,
everyone always dresses up.

492
00:38:29,338 --> 00:38:31,672
Even just to stroll
in the park. It's elegant.

493
00:38:31,674 --> 00:38:34,240
It is also July in North Carolina.

494
00:38:34,242 --> 00:38:35,642
Oh, let me show you something.
I have to show you something!

495
00:38:35,644 --> 00:38:37,210
What?

496
00:38:37,212 --> 00:38:39,212
Ruth, we're going to be late.

497
00:38:52,694 --> 00:38:55,229
It's by an artist
in Black Mountain.

498
00:38:55,231 --> 00:38:57,432
What's Black Mountain?
It's an arts college.

499
00:38:57,434 --> 00:38:59,467
A whole movement,
right here in North Carolina.

500
00:39:00,703 --> 00:39:01,635
And isn't it wonderful?

501
00:39:03,004 --> 00:39:04,738
Such a personal landscape.

502
00:39:05,606 --> 00:39:08,141
It's so direct and frank.

503
00:39:09,644 --> 00:39:12,246
Simplified and distorted.

504
00:39:12,248 --> 00:39:14,215
All at the same time.

505
00:39:14,683 --> 00:39:16,150
Don't you love it?

506
00:39:20,255 --> 00:39:22,457
I love how much
you love it.

507
00:39:29,366 --> 00:39:30,332
Come on.

508
00:39:32,932 --> 00:39:33,780
What?
No, no, no.

509
00:39:33,815 --> 00:39:35,174
Excuse me.

510
00:39:44,446 --> 00:39:46,481
All right. You want to dance?
Let's dance.

511
00:39:53,723 --> 00:39:56,191
Oh!

512
00:40:07,103 --> 00:40:08,337
Wow.

513
00:40:08,805 --> 00:40:10,572
Whoo!

514
00:40:45,276 --> 00:40:48,478
<i>That kiss, our first kiss...</i>

515
00:40:48,480 --> 00:40:51,347
<i>it was a promise
of everything to come.</i>

516
00:41:01,325 --> 00:41:03,626
<i>The days became months.</i>

517
00:41:03,628 --> 00:41:06,663
<i>We ventured on
weekends to new places.</i>

518
00:41:06,665 --> 00:41:09,432
<i>Never once had I been
on vacation.</i>

519
00:41:09,434 --> 00:41:11,234
<i>Had I, though...</i>

520
00:41:11,236 --> 00:41:14,237
<i>it could never have been
as memorable as these.</i>

521
00:41:15,339 --> 00:41:16,272
What?

522
00:41:21,413 --> 00:41:24,115
It's the first time North Carolina
has felt like home.

523
00:41:54,180 --> 00:41:56,847
But yet, with my most
important student...

524
00:41:56,849 --> 00:41:59,283
I am a total failure.

525
00:41:59,285 --> 00:42:01,485
Ruth has fallen in love
with contemporary art.

526
00:42:01,487 --> 00:42:04,255
Father thinks that art stopped
with Matisse and Picasso.

527
00:42:04,257 --> 00:42:07,391
I don't think it stopped.
But it's taken a long nap.

528
00:42:07,393 --> 00:42:09,627
You try and raise your
children right, Ira...

529
00:42:09,629 --> 00:42:12,731
and they grow up and
think for themselves.

530
00:42:12,733 --> 00:42:14,166
Very good.
Very good.

531
00:42:14,168 --> 00:42:15,233
It's tragedy!

532
00:42:20,439 --> 00:42:23,208
It was nice seeing
you talk like that.

533
00:42:23,210 --> 00:42:25,744
Nothing would make me happier
than a lifetime of days like this.

534
00:42:27,312 --> 00:42:28,713
Hey, Ruth. I need to ask
you something.

535
00:42:28,715 --> 00:42:30,248
Wait.

536
00:42:36,290 --> 00:42:38,823
I want a big family.
A really big family.

537
00:42:41,827 --> 00:42:44,262
I've always wanted one
since I was a little girl.

538
00:42:46,366 --> 00:42:48,334
With everything
that's going on now...

539
00:42:49,636 --> 00:42:51,771
I feel this need,
this responsibility,

540
00:42:51,773 --> 00:42:53,539
to bring life back
into the world.

541
00:42:56,275 --> 00:42:57,876
Sounds perfect.

542
00:43:02,448 --> 00:43:03,315
You can ask me now.

543
00:43:05,652 --> 00:43:06,919
Ruth...

544
00:43:06,921 --> 00:43:09,455
I know I'm not a rich man.

545
00:43:09,457 --> 00:43:11,457
Don't know the last
thing about art.

546
00:43:12,426 --> 00:43:13,960
All I can do is promise to love you...

547
00:43:13,962 --> 00:43:14,961
every second of every day
for the rest of my life.

548
00:43:15,862 --> 00:43:17,263
Really?

549
00:43:21,368 --> 00:43:22,236
Will you marry me?

550
00:43:22,937 --> 00:43:24,605
Yes!

551
00:43:24,607 --> 00:43:27,440
Yes, yes, yes!
What took you so long?

552
00:43:32,012 --> 00:43:33,012
Welcome to the family.

553
00:43:34,481 --> 00:43:35,681
Thank you.
So good to have you.

554
00:43:39,754 --> 00:43:42,656
"With love, Ira. "

555
00:44:05,046 --> 00:44:07,047
I'll come back tomorrow.

556
00:45:04,006 --> 00:45:05,740
Mr. Levinson?
Do I know you?

557
00:45:06,675 --> 00:45:07,875
Luke Collins.

558
00:45:09,646 --> 00:45:11,880
Remember, off 119...

559
00:45:11,882 --> 00:45:14,383
when you decided to bust
open that guard rail?

560
00:45:16,853 --> 00:45:18,854
Oh, you saved my life.

561
00:45:20,390 --> 00:45:21,123
Thank you.

562
00:45:21,491 --> 00:45:22,757
Hi.

563
00:45:25,561 --> 00:45:26,594
Hi.

564
00:45:30,924 --> 00:45:32,668
Is this your Luke?

565
00:45:32,703 --> 00:45:34,036
This is my friend Luke.

566
00:45:34,504 --> 00:45:35,671
Yes.

567
00:45:36,406 --> 00:45:37,873
Your friend. Hmm.

568
00:45:37,875 --> 00:45:39,074
Mmm-hmm.

569
00:45:42,545 --> 00:45:43,445
What are you doing here?

570
00:45:46,083 --> 00:45:49,119
I found this on
the floor of my truck.

571
00:45:49,121 --> 00:45:51,487
Figured you might wanna
hang on to that one.

572
00:45:54,090 --> 00:45:58,827
<i>December 7th, 1941.</i>

573
00:45:58,829 --> 00:46:02,698
<i>Nothing made me happier than knowing
we were going to be married.</i>

574
00:46:02,700 --> 00:46:04,834
<i>But the world you and
your family had fled...</i>

575
00:46:05,569 --> 00:46:07,971
<i>finally caught up to us.</i>

576
00:46:07,973 --> 00:46:10,673
<i>The United States
of America...</i>

577
00:46:10,675 --> 00:46:13,743
<i>was suddenly and
deliberately attacked...</i>

578
00:46:13,745 --> 00:46:16,179
<i>by Naval and Air Forces...</i>

579
00:46:16,181 --> 00:46:18,648
<i>of the Empire of Japan.</i>

580
00:46:21,552 --> 00:46:23,052
Promise me you'll come back.
I will.

581
00:46:23,054 --> 00:46:25,422
Promise me, Ira!

582
00:46:25,424 --> 00:46:26,723
I promise.

583
00:46:28,659 --> 00:46:30,427
Look at me.
I promise.

584
00:46:36,734 --> 00:46:38,635
Come back to me!

585
00:46:54,718 --> 00:46:56,019
Help!

586
00:47:03,862 --> 00:47:05,062
We can't just leave
him out there.

587
00:47:07,065 --> 00:47:09,099
Help! Help me!

588
00:47:12,704 --> 00:47:14,940
Somebody help me!

589
00:47:15,808 --> 00:47:16,641
I gotta save him.

590
00:47:18,478 --> 00:47:20,911
Are you crazy? Those Panzers
are 200 yards away.

591
00:47:20,913 --> 00:47:22,813
You'll never make it back.

592
00:47:22,815 --> 00:47:26,584
I'll make it back.
I made a promise I have to keep.

593
00:47:26,586 --> 00:47:29,520
You getting killed ain't gonna
help anyone but the Germans.

594
00:47:33,659 --> 00:47:35,227
Help me! Please!

595
00:47:36,662 --> 00:47:37,863
Oh, my God!

596
00:47:40,666 --> 00:47:42,667
Can somebody help me?

597
00:47:48,241 --> 00:47:49,206
Oh, shit.

598
00:47:56,616 --> 00:47:57,816
Put your arms around my neck.

599
00:48:04,790 --> 00:48:06,825
I gotta get back.
I gotta get back to Ruth.

600
00:48:23,576 --> 00:48:25,544
That was goddamn crazy, Levinson.
Do you know that?

601
00:48:29,016 --> 00:48:30,616
Shit!

602
00:48:38,892 --> 00:48:40,560
I'm very sorry.

603
00:49:27,108 --> 00:49:29,743
<i>When I came back from the war,
I wasn't the same.</i>

604
00:49:31,079 --> 00:49:34,181
<i>I was fighting
a bigger battle now.</i>

605
00:49:34,183 --> 00:49:37,017
<i>And I couldn't honor the
promise I had made to you.</i>

606
00:49:50,898 --> 00:49:52,633
Your mother says you've
been home since Monday.

607
00:49:59,942 --> 00:50:01,676
I can't pretend to know
what you've been through...

608
00:50:01,678 --> 00:50:03,211
but I want to help.

609
00:50:15,357 --> 00:50:17,225
Don't you think I deserve
an explanation?

610
00:50:21,730 --> 00:50:23,364
Well...

611
00:50:23,366 --> 00:50:24,932
I do.

612
00:50:40,250 --> 00:50:42,084
You don't understand.
It wasn't the injury itself.

613
00:50:42,086 --> 00:50:44,152
The wound got infected.

614
00:50:44,154 --> 00:50:46,187
I ran a high fever
for almost two weeks.

615
00:50:46,189 --> 00:50:48,456
You need to see more doctors.
Get a second opinion.

616
00:50:48,458 --> 00:50:50,893
Don't you think I've
already done that?

617
00:50:50,895 --> 00:50:52,795
There's nothing they can do.

618
00:50:54,998 --> 00:50:56,799
This is my life,
I have to accept it.

619
00:50:56,801 --> 00:50:57,866
But I don't want it
to be yours.

620
00:50:57,868 --> 00:50:59,301
But there is still a chance.

621
00:50:59,303 --> 00:51:01,770
I want to marry you.

622
00:51:01,772 --> 00:51:03,105
If you marry me,
you may never have a family.

623
00:51:04,941 --> 00:51:06,875
Are you honestly willing
to give that up?

624
00:51:36,841 --> 00:51:38,141
<i>The war was over...</i>

625
00:51:39,410 --> 00:51:40,944
<i>and as far as I
was concerned...</i>

626
00:51:41,746 --> 00:51:44,047
<i>so was my life.</i>

627
00:51:49,487 --> 00:51:50,754
We're closed!

628
00:51:53,824 --> 00:51:55,492
I know what you're doing!

629
00:51:55,494 --> 00:51:57,127
You cannot tell me what
I'm willing to give up!

630
00:51:59,296 --> 00:52:00,864
When you went to war...

631
00:52:00,866 --> 00:52:04,168
I was here,
clinging to the hope...

632
00:52:04,170 --> 00:52:06,303
that you would come home
and we would get married.

633
00:52:07,539 --> 00:52:09,807
Yes, and have kids.
But that's a dream, Ira.

634
00:52:11,777 --> 00:52:13,877
You're real.

635
00:52:13,879 --> 00:52:15,345
I don't know what
the future holds...

636
00:52:15,347 --> 00:52:17,447
but I know there's no
future without you.

637
00:52:21,853 --> 00:52:24,255
Unless you don't
love me anymore.

638
00:53:06,499 --> 00:53:08,366
<i>And in that moment...</i>

639
00:53:08,368 --> 00:53:11,302
<i>we both knew...</i>

640
00:53:11,304 --> 00:53:15,874
<i>a chance at life together was
greater than the risk of being apart.</i>

641
00:53:27,386 --> 00:53:29,287
It was really nice of you
to bring that photo.

642
00:53:30,923 --> 00:53:32,892
He sure has been through a lot.

643
00:53:32,894 --> 00:53:33,893
Yeah.

644
00:53:36,930 --> 00:53:38,097
Uh...

645
00:53:38,099 --> 00:53:39,599
Well, you take it easy.

646
00:53:41,467 --> 00:53:42,400
Luke.

647
00:53:49,376 --> 00:53:50,977
It was really good to see you.

648
00:53:56,984 --> 00:53:58,985
What are you doing right now?

649
00:54:01,255 --> 00:54:02,521
That looks good.

650
00:54:02,523 --> 00:54:04,023
Yeah.

651
00:54:04,025 --> 00:54:05,524
- I'm ready.
- All right.

652
00:54:05,526 --> 00:54:07,594
I'm so ready.

653
00:54:07,596 --> 00:54:10,602
- I'll give you the little stick.
- Thank you. - Yeah.

654
00:54:10,927 --> 00:54:12,553
Ladies first.

655
00:54:13,234 --> 00:54:16,903
I'm still getting used to your
Southern gentlemanly ways.

656
00:54:16,905 --> 00:54:18,371
I'm still trying to impress you.

657
00:54:20,107 --> 00:54:21,941
It's kind of working.

658
00:54:21,943 --> 00:54:23,542
A little.
Mmm...

659
00:54:23,544 --> 00:54:26,179
Just don't let me win.

660
00:54:26,181 --> 00:54:28,115
I enjoy good,
healthy competition.

661
00:54:28,117 --> 00:54:29,049
Noted.

662
00:54:37,526 --> 00:54:39,292
What are you doing?

663
00:54:39,294 --> 00:54:40,426
You told me not
to let you win.

664
00:54:41,428 --> 00:54:44,998
So I'm going with plan B.
Distraction.

665
00:54:45,000 --> 00:54:46,333
Hmm.

666
00:54:46,335 --> 00:54:47,601
Mmm-hmm.

667
00:54:53,574 --> 00:54:55,008
Yes!

668
00:54:55,010 --> 00:54:57,577
Yes! Sorry!

669
00:54:57,579 --> 00:54:58,312
- Oh, thank you.
- Thank you very much.

670
00:54:58,314 --> 00:55:01,582
Oh, I love mac and cheese.

671
00:55:01,584 --> 00:55:02,717
Comfort food?

672
00:55:03,085 --> 00:55:04,052
Yeah.

673
00:55:05,287 --> 00:55:06,187
What's your comfort food?

674
00:55:08,589 --> 00:55:10,590
Kolduny.

675
00:55:10,592 --> 00:55:12,292
Kol-what?
Kolduny.

676
00:55:12,294 --> 00:55:14,361
They're these super,
super delicious...

677
00:55:14,363 --> 00:55:16,430
Polish meat dumplings
that my mom makes.

678
00:55:17,432 --> 00:55:19,067
We serve them at the diner...

679
00:55:19,069 --> 00:55:21,970
and I promise you,
with one bite of those...

680
00:55:21,972 --> 00:55:23,371
it would put your mac
and cheese to shame.

681
00:55:23,373 --> 00:55:24,605
Is that an invitation?

682
00:55:26,608 --> 00:55:27,675
Maybe.

683
00:55:29,211 --> 00:55:30,378
Oh. No, no.
Help yourself.

684
00:55:30,380 --> 00:55:31,646
No!
Yeah.

685
00:55:31,648 --> 00:55:34,015
Just a bite.

686
00:55:34,017 --> 00:55:35,249
When did your parents
come to the States?

687
00:55:35,251 --> 00:55:36,485
Uh, before I was born.

688
00:55:37,753 --> 00:55:39,554
That's crazy.
I couldn't have done that.

689
00:55:39,556 --> 00:55:42,156
Really?
No.

690
00:55:42,158 --> 00:55:45,026
You ride bulls for a living.
You could do anything.

691
00:55:45,028 --> 00:55:47,328
Riding bulls has got nothing on
moving clear across the world.

692
00:55:47,330 --> 00:55:49,230
What?
Yeah.

693
00:55:49,232 --> 00:55:51,232
Your parents had to
adjust their whole life.

694
00:55:51,234 --> 00:55:53,368
No, they didn't
adjust anything.

695
00:55:54,604 --> 00:55:57,206
Growing up with
immigrant parents,

696
00:55:57,208 --> 00:55:59,541
my life was always
really different.

697
00:55:59,543 --> 00:56:02,011
Everyone was always screaming
in weird languages...

698
00:56:02,013 --> 00:56:04,313
I brought smelly,
strange snacks to school.

699
00:56:04,315 --> 00:56:06,714
My pants were
too short always.

700
00:56:07,516 --> 00:56:09,650
Pants still are too short.

701
00:56:09,652 --> 00:56:12,153
Growing up on a cattle ranch,
everybody I knew was the same.

702
00:56:12,155 --> 00:56:16,258
Everybody you know is fourth
generation cattle ranchers.

703
00:56:16,260 --> 00:56:18,694
I'm jealous.
Why?

704
00:56:18,696 --> 00:56:20,529
I wanted to be like everyone
else when I was little.

705
00:56:22,699 --> 00:56:26,301
The reason I like you is because
you're nothing like everyone else.

706
00:56:29,639 --> 00:56:31,608
You're not so bad yourself.

707
00:56:34,545 --> 00:56:37,780
I think before I met you,
the closest thing I came to cattle was...

708
00:56:37,782 --> 00:56:39,348
steak.

709
00:56:39,350 --> 00:56:41,750
Steak? Time to get you
on a bull, then.

710
00:56:41,752 --> 00:56:43,118
A bull?
Yeah.

711
00:56:43,120 --> 00:56:44,353
No way!

712
00:56:44,355 --> 00:56:45,721
One bull, one time.

713
00:56:45,723 --> 00:56:48,123
No! How about one horse,
one time?

714
00:56:48,793 --> 00:56:50,160
We could do that.

715
00:56:50,162 --> 00:56:51,528
Next week.
Okay.

716
00:56:54,632 --> 00:56:57,400
Ooh. I've got an idea.
Uh-oh.

717
00:56:57,402 --> 00:56:58,635
It's so good.
What?

718
00:56:58,637 --> 00:57:00,703
So good!
Come on!

719
00:57:00,705 --> 00:57:02,272
What?
Where am I going?

720
00:57:02,274 --> 00:57:04,607
Where are we going?
You'll see.

721
00:57:04,609 --> 00:57:06,609
After you.
Wow. Thank you.

722
00:57:08,179 --> 00:57:09,446
Ready?

723
00:57:11,782 --> 00:57:13,249
Crazy face.
Yeah.

724
00:57:39,844 --> 00:57:41,811
Yeah, that looks good.

725
00:57:43,381 --> 00:57:44,582
Thank you.

726
00:57:49,187 --> 00:57:50,488
Okay.

727
00:57:51,757 --> 00:57:53,124
There you go.
Whoa.

728
00:57:55,294 --> 00:57:56,660
Put your feet in.
Grab the reins.

729
00:58:04,870 --> 00:58:06,770
You ready?
Yeah.

730
00:58:06,772 --> 00:58:08,639
Pull back on those reins.

731
00:58:08,641 --> 00:58:09,773
Come on.

732
00:58:11,443 --> 00:58:13,911
Hey, there we go!

733
00:58:13,913 --> 00:58:17,414
Oh, whoa, we're going backwards!
This is awesome!

734
00:58:17,416 --> 00:58:18,750
Yeah, there you go, just like that.
Lay your hands down.

735
00:58:18,752 --> 00:58:19,718
Okay.

736
00:58:26,527 --> 00:58:28,393
How are you doing that?

737
00:58:28,395 --> 00:58:29,494
Why am I bouncing so much?

738
00:58:30,396 --> 00:58:32,230
Ease up on those
reins a little bit.

739
00:58:32,232 --> 00:58:33,497
All right.

740
00:58:46,746 --> 00:58:48,680
Atta girl!

741
00:58:48,682 --> 00:58:50,348
I don't think you
can keep up with me!

742
00:59:05,898 --> 00:59:07,332
You know,
I have to admit

743
00:59:07,334 --> 00:59:09,634
you're pretty good
on a horse.

744
00:59:09,636 --> 00:59:10,502
Well, thank you.

745
00:59:14,441 --> 00:59:16,442
But I don't know...

746
00:59:16,444 --> 00:59:18,678
I bet you couldn't beat
me to the barn.

747
00:59:18,680 --> 00:59:20,413
Oh, I wouldn't go that way!
Whoa!

748
00:59:20,415 --> 00:59:21,247
Oh!

749
00:59:22,784 --> 00:59:23,849
Oh, my God!

750
00:59:25,986 --> 00:59:27,653
Oh, my God!

751
00:59:30,258 --> 00:59:32,325
Come here.

752
00:59:32,327 --> 00:59:33,559
I tried to tell you.

753
00:59:33,561 --> 00:59:34,827
I know you did.

754
00:59:37,598 --> 00:59:39,665
Well, this is, um...
This is home.

755
00:59:39,667 --> 00:59:41,801
Wow.
This is nice.

756
00:59:42,569 --> 00:59:44,570
Really nice.
Yeah.

757
00:59:44,572 --> 00:59:46,639
Oh, the shower's right in there,

758
00:59:46,641 --> 00:59:48,275
and there should be towels
and everything.

759
00:59:48,277 --> 00:59:49,009
Okay.

760
00:59:50,678 --> 00:59:52,312
Hey, uh, Sophia?

761
00:59:52,314 --> 00:59:54,281
Did you want soup?

762
00:59:54,949 --> 00:59:56,283
Oh, you make soup, too?

763
00:59:58,553 --> 01:00:00,454
Kind of.

764
01:00:00,456 --> 01:00:01,954
Soup, soup, soup...

765
01:00:16,537 --> 01:00:17,938
Oh, my God.

766
01:01:49,065 --> 01:01:50,099
Come on.

767
01:01:55,072 --> 01:01:56,406
There you go.

768
01:01:57,508 --> 01:01:58,407
Put your hands right here.

769
01:02:01,444 --> 01:02:03,078
The goal's pretty simple.

770
01:02:03,080 --> 01:02:04,079
All you gotta do is hang
on for eight seconds.

771
01:02:14,425 --> 01:02:15,859
Wow!

772
01:02:15,861 --> 01:02:17,060
There's nothing to it.

773
01:02:18,662 --> 01:02:20,597
Yeah, some bulls
are nice like that.

774
01:02:21,966 --> 01:02:23,566
This is...
Yeah, okay.

775
01:02:23,568 --> 01:02:24,834
Excuse us, sorry.

776
01:02:25,469 --> 01:02:26,436
Sorry.

777
01:02:37,982 --> 01:02:39,682
So how do you know which
one you're gonna get?

778
01:02:39,684 --> 01:02:41,084
You don't.

779
01:02:41,086 --> 01:02:43,520
<i>You pick from a bowl.</i>

780
01:02:43,522 --> 01:02:46,991
<i>And the fan favorite from Walkertown,
North Carolina...</i>

781
01:02:46,993 --> 01:02:49,460
<i>Luke Collins!</i>

782
01:02:49,462 --> 01:02:52,463
<i>Number four is the chip
you selected...</i>

783
01:02:52,465 --> 01:02:53,697
<i>and that is Gunpowder
and Lead, Luke.</i>

784
01:02:54,966 --> 01:02:57,100
<i>Jared Middleton reaching in...</i>

785
01:02:57,102 --> 01:02:58,868
<i>and pulling out chip
number two.</i>

786
01:02:58,870 --> 01:03:00,603
<i>You have Asteroid.</i>

787
01:03:02,473 --> 01:03:03,840
Whoa... Whoa!

788
01:03:03,842 --> 01:03:06,076
That's impossible!
Yeah!

789
01:03:06,078 --> 01:03:07,812
You can only touch
with your riding hand.

790
01:03:07,814 --> 01:03:09,146
All other touching's
against the rules.

791
01:03:09,148 --> 01:03:11,816
Okay.
I got it.

792
01:03:20,826 --> 01:03:21,792
Let's go!

793
01:03:46,919 --> 01:03:48,920
If you are off balance even a little,
you lose points.

794
01:03:50,590 --> 01:03:52,791
<i>But if you control the bull,
you get style points.</i>

795
01:03:55,627 --> 01:03:56,927
Is that how you do
the hand? That?

796
01:03:57,629 --> 01:03:58,763
More or less.

797
01:04:07,974 --> 01:04:12,043
The bull is judged too,
on speed, agility and power.

798
01:04:12,045 --> 01:04:14,679
<i>Whether it bucks or blows out,
turns back around on you.</i>

799
01:04:28,594 --> 01:04:29,728
Yeah!

800
01:04:45,679 --> 01:04:46,679
Some bulls are just plain mean.

801
01:04:47,080 --> 01:04:48,214
And others...

802
01:04:51,051 --> 01:04:52,553
<i>Others are monsters.</i>

803
01:04:56,189 --> 01:04:58,090
Let's brave the storm.

804
01:04:58,092 --> 01:04:59,158
Let's do it.

805
01:05:10,672 --> 01:05:12,906
This is certainly better
than the hospital, isn't it?

806
01:05:17,145 --> 01:05:18,145
How are you feeling?

807
01:05:19,781 --> 01:05:21,882
The better question is,
how do I look?

808
01:05:22,883 --> 01:05:24,617
Very handsome.

809
01:05:24,619 --> 01:05:26,319
All I care about.

810
01:05:27,788 --> 01:05:29,222
Hold on one second.

811
01:05:29,224 --> 01:05:30,724
Hello?

812
01:05:30,726 --> 01:05:31,892
<i>Hi, Sophia.
This is Adrienne.</i>

813
01:05:31,894 --> 01:05:33,794
Hi, Ms. Francis.

814
01:05:33,796 --> 01:05:35,762
<i>My client has an exhibit
in Charlotte next weekend.</i>

815
01:05:35,764 --> 01:05:37,064
<i>Can you be there?</i>

816
01:05:37,066 --> 01:05:38,865
Yeah, I'd love to.
That sounds great.

817
01:05:38,867 --> 01:05:39,700
<i>This could be a real
opportunity for us.</i>

818
01:05:39,702 --> 01:05:40,934
Okay.

819
01:05:40,936 --> 01:05:42,169
<i>I'll email you
the details.</i>

820
01:05:42,171 --> 01:05:43,070
Okay. All right,
I'll talk to you soon.

821
01:05:43,072 --> 01:05:44,204
<i>Bye, Sophia.</i>

822
01:05:44,206 --> 01:05:45,138
Thanks, bye.

823
01:05:46,675 --> 01:05:47,642
Good news?

824
01:05:47,943 --> 01:05:49,010
Yeah.

825
01:05:49,012 --> 01:05:49,978
Um...

826
01:05:51,280 --> 01:05:53,280
The woman I'm working for
this summer...

827
01:05:53,282 --> 01:05:55,148
she has a client with an
art exhibit in Charlotte...

828
01:05:55,150 --> 01:05:56,984
and wants me to help her out.

829
01:05:56,986 --> 01:05:58,952
I didn't know you had
an interest in art.

830
01:05:58,954 --> 01:06:01,655
Only since I was, like, five.

831
01:06:01,657 --> 01:06:04,692
Ruth also loved art.
Yeah.

832
01:06:04,694 --> 01:06:08,229
Yeah, I remember the story with
the painting in the hotel lobby.

833
01:06:08,231 --> 01:06:10,932
You've heard of Black
Mountain College?

834
01:06:13,202 --> 01:06:15,637
I'm doing my senior
thesis on it right now.

835
01:06:15,639 --> 01:06:17,839
That's where I was headed...

836
01:06:17,841 --> 01:06:19,340
when I got in that fight
with the guardrail.

837
01:06:23,312 --> 01:06:25,113
Are you sure this is how you
want to spend your honeymoon?

838
01:06:25,115 --> 01:06:26,214
Oh, I promise you're going
to love it, I promise!

839
01:06:28,151 --> 01:06:30,184
I'd rather we'd just
stayed in bed.

840
01:06:49,673 --> 01:06:52,674
<i>You weren't able to engage your
passion for contemporary art...</i>

841
01:06:52,676 --> 01:06:53,741
<i>in our little town...</i>

842
01:06:56,412 --> 01:06:58,147
<i>so Black Mountain College
was a godsend.</i>

843
01:07:02,852 --> 01:07:04,753
It's so amazing!

844
01:07:09,292 --> 01:07:12,695
Really look at your work
to understand it.

845
01:07:12,697 --> 01:07:15,230
But I want to be able to
control the accidents...

846
01:07:15,232 --> 01:07:17,767
and not leave them to fate...

847
01:07:17,769 --> 01:07:19,135
or the Lord or chance,
whatever you want to call it.

848
01:07:20,937 --> 01:07:22,871
I teach you to see.

849
01:07:22,873 --> 01:07:25,040
Then even an accident
will have purpose...

850
01:07:26,376 --> 01:07:27,976
and direction.

851
01:07:33,851 --> 01:07:36,386
Oh, I love it!

852
01:07:36,388 --> 01:07:38,488
For over 500 years, artists have
been reproducing...

853
01:07:38,490 --> 01:07:40,890
quite literally what they
see in front of them.

854
01:07:40,892 --> 01:07:43,126
Then Kandinsky came and broke
all the rules, all of them!

855
01:07:45,062 --> 01:07:47,097
Sorry.

856
01:07:47,099 --> 01:07:48,865
I love it!

857
01:07:57,441 --> 01:07:59,809
I can't believe we met
Josef Albers today.

858
01:08:05,950 --> 01:08:07,484
It's just a bit further.

859
01:08:10,990 --> 01:08:12,857
You all right?

860
01:08:12,859 --> 01:08:14,158
Oh!

861
01:08:18,163 --> 01:08:19,195
You ready?

862
01:08:19,363 --> 01:08:20,363
Yeah.

863
01:08:24,902 --> 01:08:26,202
You like it?

864
01:08:27,874 --> 01:08:29,507
<i>From one happy day
to the next...</i>

865
01:08:29,509 --> 01:08:34,378
<i>we began the process
of creating a life together.</i>

866
01:08:34,380 --> 01:08:35,446
Doesn't look like
anyone's home.

867
01:08:35,448 --> 01:08:37,448
No, I don't think
you should go in.

868
01:08:37,450 --> 01:08:39,183
Ira!
What?

869
01:08:39,185 --> 01:08:40,918
Well, let's just use the key.

870
01:08:42,088 --> 01:08:44,121
No!
Oh, my God!

871
01:08:45,858 --> 01:08:47,392
You wonderful person!

872
01:08:47,394 --> 01:08:48,793
Wait, wait, wait.
Come here.

873
01:08:52,230 --> 01:08:53,230
Yeah, there.

874
01:08:56,568 --> 01:08:57,501
No.

875
01:08:58,370 --> 01:08:59,336
There.

876
01:09:04,343 --> 01:09:07,212
There! First thing you see
when you come in!

877
01:09:07,214 --> 01:09:09,447
<i>Life was busy
and happy for us.</i>

878
01:09:09,449 --> 01:09:12,818
<i>I took over my dad's
booming business...</i>

879
01:09:12,820 --> 01:09:15,921
<i>and you found a job
teaching at the local school.</i>

880
01:09:15,923 --> 01:09:17,454
Who understands this, huh?

881
01:09:17,456 --> 01:09:19,156
Oh! Look at this!

882
01:09:19,158 --> 01:09:21,960
You're all on your way to
becoming math geniuses.

883
01:09:21,962 --> 01:09:24,062
Solve the problems
on the board.

884
01:09:24,064 --> 01:09:26,932
If you have any questions,
please ask.

885
01:09:26,934 --> 01:09:28,967
Wow, it sounds like you
made her very happy.

886
01:09:30,169 --> 01:09:31,403
I did.

887
01:09:32,505 --> 01:09:34,272
For a while.

888
01:09:36,943 --> 01:09:38,945
His first cowboy hat.

889
01:09:38,947 --> 01:09:40,313
That is so cute!

890
01:09:40,315 --> 01:09:41,180
Never took it off.

891
01:09:42,015 --> 01:09:43,115
He ate in it.

892
01:09:43,117 --> 01:09:45,051
He slept in it.

893
01:09:45,053 --> 01:09:46,618
He even tried to glue it to his
head so it wouldn't come off!

894
01:09:46,620 --> 01:09:48,086
Mom!

895
01:09:48,088 --> 01:09:49,020
What?

896
01:09:51,090 --> 01:09:53,992
He broke his arm riding a calf
when he was seven.

897
01:09:53,994 --> 01:09:56,595
I found him sneaking into the
barn at night to practice...

898
01:09:56,597 --> 01:09:59,498
hanging on with his
non-cast arm.

899
01:09:59,500 --> 01:10:00,900
Even then, I couldn't get him to
stop riding when he shouldn't.

900
01:10:04,872 --> 01:10:06,405
Hey. There you go.

901
01:10:06,407 --> 01:10:08,207
Thank you.

902
01:10:08,209 --> 01:10:09,308
Sweet.

903
01:10:14,114 --> 01:10:16,382
That's Luke's dad, Jack.

904
01:10:16,384 --> 01:10:17,583
He was a great man.
Mmm-hmm.

905
01:10:17,585 --> 01:10:19,218
Great rider, too.

906
01:10:21,321 --> 01:10:23,890
Even if you stop now, you'd still
have a better career than he had.

907
01:10:27,194 --> 01:10:28,194
What happened?

908
01:10:29,096 --> 01:10:31,097
He died of a heart attack.

909
01:10:31,099 --> 01:10:32,466
Yeah, almost five years
ago now.

910
01:10:35,904 --> 01:10:38,438
How about a little dessert?

911
01:10:38,440 --> 01:10:41,208
Luke, wait till you see
what I made for you.

912
01:10:41,210 --> 01:10:43,343
Sophia, it's worth the calories.

913
01:10:47,281 --> 01:10:48,214
No.

914
01:10:55,123 --> 01:10:56,690
How come your mom keeps talking
about you giving up riding?

915
01:10:59,027 --> 01:11:01,395
She's just being an
overprotective mom.

916
01:11:03,231 --> 01:11:04,998
How bad did you get hurt?

917
01:11:05,000 --> 01:11:06,433
Sophia...
No.

918
01:11:06,435 --> 01:11:08,201
I know all riders are
bound to get hurt.

919
01:11:08,203 --> 01:11:10,104
It's not a matter of
"if" but "when. "

920
01:11:10,106 --> 01:11:11,639
That's right.

921
01:11:11,641 --> 01:11:13,474
They say all bull riders are
either stupid or crazy.

922
01:11:13,476 --> 01:11:15,175
Yeah, and which one are you?

923
01:11:18,179 --> 01:11:20,414
I don't know.
I guess a little of both.

924
01:11:21,282 --> 01:11:23,350
What are you doing?

925
01:11:23,352 --> 01:11:27,388
This is a new painting by an artist
that Adrienne Francis represents.

926
01:11:27,390 --> 01:11:29,390
You know, the woman
I'm interning for?

927
01:11:29,392 --> 01:11:31,025
$80 grand, really?

928
01:11:32,261 --> 01:11:33,261
A lot of people
think he's a genius.

929
01:11:34,229 --> 01:11:36,297
Yeah,
he most certainly is...

930
01:11:36,299 --> 01:11:39,000
getting people to fork over
$80 grand for that.

931
01:11:43,072 --> 01:11:46,374
Are you sure that you wanna go to
this gallery showing in Charlotte?

932
01:11:46,376 --> 01:11:47,709
You want me to, right?

933
01:11:47,711 --> 01:11:48,609
Of course.

934
01:11:49,278 --> 01:11:51,112
Then I'll be there.

935
01:11:51,114 --> 01:11:52,747
Yeah, but you're riding
that afternoon.

936
01:11:52,749 --> 01:11:54,315
I'll be there.

937
01:12:09,132 --> 01:12:11,367
Wow!
Don't you look nice!

938
01:12:12,535 --> 01:12:15,169
Never seen you in a
coat and tie before.

939
01:12:15,171 --> 01:12:17,305
Yeah, doesn't happen too often.

940
01:12:18,707 --> 01:12:21,577
Oh, that's my boss,
Adrienne Francis.

941
01:12:21,579 --> 01:12:22,678
I gotta go.
Okay?

942
01:12:22,680 --> 01:12:24,446
Yeah.
Go.

943
01:12:26,416 --> 01:12:29,418
Hi. Sophia.
Nice to meet you.

944
01:12:29,420 --> 01:12:31,053
Hopefully, Sophia will be joining
me in New York, and my team.

945
01:12:35,325 --> 01:12:38,228
You usually find these sort of things
in process art or lenticular prints...

946
01:12:38,230 --> 01:12:41,331
but it's very rare in brushwork.

947
01:12:41,333 --> 01:12:43,699
That is what makes
this piece so special.

948
01:13:06,123 --> 01:13:07,657
If you have any questions,
let me know. Thank you.

949
01:13:09,693 --> 01:13:11,194
Excuse me.

950
01:13:11,196 --> 01:13:12,127
Just one second.

951
01:13:16,300 --> 01:13:18,101
It'll be worth twice that
a year from now.

952
01:13:18,103 --> 01:13:20,303
At $20,000, it's a steal.

953
01:13:20,305 --> 01:13:21,805
- Sure.
- Good.

954
01:13:21,807 --> 01:13:23,173
Do you wanna get it?

955
01:13:23,175 --> 01:13:24,407
Let's do it.
Okay.

956
01:13:33,385 --> 01:13:35,553
I'll fly you to New York.
See the space, meet the team.

957
01:13:35,555 --> 01:13:37,088
Yes!

958
01:13:37,090 --> 01:13:38,589
These are some
very important people.

959
01:13:38,591 --> 01:13:41,191
So if you can't do it, don't say yes.
No...

960
01:13:41,193 --> 01:13:43,093
I know you have finals
and other commitments.

961
01:13:43,095 --> 01:13:45,595
I'd love to. This is the most
important thing to me.

962
01:13:46,564 --> 01:13:48,131
Oh!
Uh, Luke, hi.

963
01:13:48,133 --> 01:13:50,401
This is Adrienne Francis.

964
01:13:50,403 --> 01:13:52,570
Adrienne, this is
my boyfriend, Luke.

965
01:13:54,473 --> 01:13:56,440
Are you in college with Sophia?

966
01:13:56,442 --> 01:13:58,175
No, never made it to college.

967
01:13:58,177 --> 01:14:02,113
I've never met a professional
bull rider before.

968
01:14:02,115 --> 01:14:03,547
Probably not too many
in Manhattan.

969
01:14:05,217 --> 01:14:07,652
Are you an art lover,
like Sophia?

970
01:14:07,654 --> 01:14:09,187
No, I can't say that I am.

971
01:14:10,856 --> 01:14:12,223
What did you think of tonight?

972
01:14:13,325 --> 01:14:14,291
Honestly?

973
01:14:15,260 --> 01:14:16,360
Of course.

974
01:14:18,697 --> 01:14:20,231
I think there's more bullshit
here than where I work.

975
01:14:33,379 --> 01:14:35,347
I like him.
Keep this one.

976
01:14:42,254 --> 01:14:43,722
How could you say that to her?

977
01:14:44,657 --> 01:14:46,491
It was a joke.

978
01:14:46,493 --> 01:14:48,894
To the woman who's
gonna be my boss?

979
01:14:48,896 --> 01:14:50,896
To the woman who I hope
is gonna launch my career?

980
01:14:50,898 --> 01:14:53,431
That lady? Come on.
No, you come on.

981
01:14:53,433 --> 01:14:56,501
You know how hard I have just
tried to fit into your world.

982
01:14:56,503 --> 01:14:57,636
Why can't you try to
fit into mine?

983
01:14:57,638 --> 01:14:58,770
I do!

984
01:15:00,773 --> 01:15:02,942
It was a joke, okay?
She thought it was funny.

985
01:15:02,944 --> 01:15:04,744
She laughed.
You don't know that.

986
01:15:04,746 --> 01:15:06,212
What if she was just trying
to be polite?

987
01:15:07,347 --> 01:15:08,481
Does this make sense?

988
01:15:09,215 --> 01:15:10,649
What?

989
01:15:10,651 --> 01:15:12,751
How are we gonna
make this work, huh?

990
01:15:12,753 --> 01:15:14,553
Do you really see yourself
living on a ranch?

991
01:15:14,555 --> 01:15:15,754
Working a ranch
the rest of your life?

992
01:15:17,323 --> 01:15:18,823
And what am I gonna do?

993
01:15:19,760 --> 01:15:22,328
Move to Manhattan?

994
01:15:22,330 --> 01:15:24,197
Go out with your artist friends?
Go to brunch?

995
01:15:24,199 --> 01:15:25,765
Talk about squiggly lines
on a white canvas...

996
01:15:25,767 --> 01:15:27,300
like they're more than squiggly
lines on a white canvas?

997
01:15:27,302 --> 01:15:29,769
I know all of that, I do.
I get it.

998
01:15:43,617 --> 01:15:44,517
I just...

999
01:15:46,887 --> 01:15:48,688
I just don't know how
to make this work.

1000
01:15:49,356 --> 01:15:50,957
I don't know either.

1001
01:15:52,259 --> 01:15:53,926
But I know that I want to.

1002
01:16:15,950 --> 01:16:17,818
Are we just crazy?

1003
01:16:19,420 --> 01:16:21,588
Do you think it could
work between us?

1004
01:16:22,790 --> 01:16:25,559
We just come from
such different worlds.

1005
01:16:27,328 --> 01:16:30,831
But I've never felt this way
about anybody before.

1006
01:16:32,001 --> 01:16:33,434
Not everybody gets that.

1007
01:16:34,703 --> 01:16:35,903
You did.

1008
01:16:39,340 --> 01:16:40,307
It wasn't that simple.

1009
01:16:45,647 --> 01:16:47,514
<i>As the years went by...</i>

1010
01:16:47,516 --> 01:16:50,451
<i>I could see how much
she wanted to start a family.</i>

1011
01:16:51,954 --> 01:16:54,389
<i>We tried to adopt.</i>

1012
01:16:54,391 --> 01:16:56,457
<i>But it wasn't so easy
back then.</i>

1013
01:17:21,917 --> 01:17:24,052
Now, today we're
going to learn...

1014
01:17:25,622 --> 01:17:26,689
about my favorite...

1015
01:17:27,857 --> 01:17:29,925
book.

1016
01:17:29,927 --> 01:17:31,760
<i>It's called Pippi Longstocking.</i>

1017
01:17:53,417 --> 01:17:55,351
If anyone teases him about this,

1018
01:17:55,353 --> 01:17:56,785
they'll have me to deal with.

1019
01:18:13,069 --> 01:18:14,670
Good morning.

1020
01:18:20,511 --> 01:18:22,479
Hello.

1021
01:18:22,481 --> 01:18:25,081
My name is Ruth Levinson.
I'm Daniel's teacher.

1022
01:18:27,385 --> 01:18:29,886
I came here because
I'm slightly concerned.

1023
01:18:29,888 --> 01:18:31,521
He's falling asleep in class.

1024
01:18:31,523 --> 01:18:33,722
<i>We were surprised to learn...</i>

1025
01:18:33,724 --> 01:18:37,994
<i>that Daniel McDonald was being
raised by a half-brother and his wife.</i>

1026
01:18:37,996 --> 01:18:40,130
<i>Neither seemed to care
if he ate or starved.</i>

1027
01:18:40,132 --> 01:18:43,466
He's a very bright boy.

1028
01:18:43,468 --> 01:18:45,001
Infinite potential.

1029
01:18:45,003 --> 01:18:47,937
Maybe I could tutor
him after class?

1030
01:18:47,939 --> 01:18:48,838
All right.

1031
01:18:49,740 --> 01:18:50,840
Yes?

1032
01:19:37,377 --> 01:19:38,833
Are you a wolf?

1033
01:19:39,571 --> 01:19:41,138
No, ma'am.

1034
01:19:43,587 --> 01:19:45,230
Are you a bear?

1035
01:19:45,403 --> 01:19:47,653
- No, ma'am.
- Oh.

1036
01:19:47,688 --> 01:19:49,534
Are you a boy?

1037
01:19:49,936 --> 01:19:51,102
Yes, ma'am.

1038
01:19:52,038 --> 01:19:54,806
Boys use knives and forks.

1039
01:20:05,684 --> 01:20:06,818
Oh. Almost.

1040
01:20:07,553 --> 01:20:10,155
Yeah.
Okay.

1041
01:20:10,157 --> 01:20:13,158
What star is that?

1042
01:20:13,160 --> 01:20:15,126
The North Star, Polaris.

1043
01:20:15,128 --> 01:20:16,761
Good. Look.

1044
